    a widower who had at least six daughters: Isabel (who became mrs Sholto Douglas, see <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="DOU02">Douglas</persName> entry), Rosa, Louisa, Julia, Ellen, and Elise Agnes.  He also 
 had a number of sons and grandsons whom MWS knew less well. They included George, Julian (at Cambridge with Percy Florence), Alfred, and Charles.
 The family are associated with residence at Park Cottage, Paddington. </p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">All Robinsons 1801-1824 are taken to be  
referring to the publishing family as this is prior to Mary Shelley's - and, it is assumed, Godwin's - acquaintance with this other Robinson family.  As the nature of the 
calls change from the more commercial 'call on' to 'dines at' at this period, it is deemed relatively easy to distinguish between the contacts with both families. </p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">On 23 February 1811 there is a reference to a 'Mrs Robinson', which may possibly be connected to this family, but this has not been coded.</p></note><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="other"><title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">DNB</title>.</bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="printedbook"><title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">The journals of Mary Shelley, 1814â€“1844</title>, ed. by Paula R. Feldman and Diana 
